---
import DocsLayout from "../../layouts/DocsLayout.astro";
import { languageRows } from "../../facts";
---

<DocsLayout
  title="Languages & graph · Squeezy docs"
  description="The 15 languages Squeezy understands locally, what the code graph gives you, and how unsupported files are handled."
  activeDoc="/docs/languages/"
  eyebrow="coverage"
  heading="Languages & the code graph."
  lead="For supported languages, Squeezy understands your code on your machine, declarations, references, and structure, instead of guessing from raw text."
>
  <section class="doc-block">
    <div class="doc-prose">
      <h2>When Squeezy understands your code vs when it guesses</h2>
      <p>
        For the 15 languages below, Squeezy builds a local map of your code and
        navigates it directly: it can find where something is declared, who
        calls it, and how files relate, then read just the relevant lines. Each
        result is grounded in your actual source rather than a guess.
      </p>
      <p>
        Files outside this list still work. They fall back to bounded search,
        targeted reads, shell commands, and verifier tools, just without the
        graph-backed navigation.
      </p>
    </div>
  </section>

  <section class="doc-block">
    <h2>Supported languages</h2>
    <div class="matrix compact-matrix">
      {
        languageRows.map((row) => (
          <article class="matrix-row">
            <h3>{row.name}</h3>
            <p>{row.detail}</p>
          </article>
        ))
      }
    </div>
    <p class="footnote">
      Under the hood these map to 13 parser families (C and C++ share a family,
      as do JavaScript and TypeScript). Coverage maturity varies by language.
    </p>
  </section>
</DocsLayout>
